 <header>
            <h2>What is selector’s specificity and who it’s calculated?</h2>
          </header>
          <div>
            <p>A selector's specificity is a way to determine which style rules are applied to an element when there are multiple conflicting rules. Specificity is calculated based on different factors, including the type of selector used and any additional modifiers such as classes, IDs, or inline styles. The specificity is represented in a numerical value, where higher values indicate higher specificity.
</p>
          </div>
          <footer>
            <p><a href="#link">[link]</a></p>
			</footer>
			<header>
            <h2>What are complex selectors?</h2>
          </header>
          <div>
            <p>Complex selectors are selectors that are more specific and target elements based on multiple conditions. They can include combinations of different types of selectors, such as descendant selectors, child selectors, attribute selectors, and pseudo-classes.
</p>
          </div>
          <footer>
            <p><a href="#link">[link]</a></p>
			</footer>
			<header>
            <h2>What is the difference between pseudo-classes and pseudo-elements?</h2>
          </header>
          <div>
            <p>Pseudo-classes are used to style elements based on their state or position in the document. They are denoted by a colon followed by the pseudo-class name, such as :hover or :first-child. Pseudo-elements, on the other hand, allow styling of specific parts of an element, such as the first line of a paragraph or the first letter of a word. Pseudo-elements are denoted by a double colon followed by the pseudo-element name, such as ::before or ::after.</p>
                    <h1>Paragraphs</h1>
